article.headline: Andrews scores her 15 in second half
article.linkText: When push came to shove, Sooners pull away
article.story:
NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- When Kansas State did a little extra
shoving, Oklahoma pushed back and got the win.

Dionnah Jackson scored 18 points, Laura Andrews added 15 -- all
in the second half -- and the Sooners responded to a Kansas State
player's push in the back by rushing away with a 77-61 win Sunday.

Claire Coggins made two free throws with 17:17 to play to bring
the 16th-ranked Wildcats (17-5, 8-3 Big 12) within 44-37, but she
got Oklahoma (13-9, 5-6) fired up in the process. After Lauren
Shoush fouled Coggins on a fastbreak layup try, Coggins shoved
Shoush in the back, but no foul was called.

After Coggins hit her foul shots, Andrews drilled a 3-pointer
from the left wing, Jackson scored on a fastbreak, and Erin Higgins
hit a 3-pointer that bounced twice on the rim and banked off the
backboard before falling in.

"I think that was the point that we came together," Jackson
said.

After the confrontation, Oklahoma's players didn't say anything.
They let their play stand as the response.

"I think we read each other's minds like 'No, not in our
house," Jackson said. "We don't let that happen to one of our
teammates.

"She apologized and everything, and I think it was just in the
heat of the moment, but still we took advantage of it."

Shoush stole the ball on the Wildcats' next possession and
rushed downcourt for the finish. When a foul was called, too, she
pumped both fists in the air.

Two possessions later, she made another steal and converted a
layup for a 58-39 lead. Oklahoma kept pulling away.

Jackson scored underneath and Andrews had five straight points --
a 3-pointer from the left side and a double-pump layup -- to make it
65-41.

Kansas State coach Deb Patterson thought the shove made a
difference, too.

"It seemed like momentum really shifted at that point,"
Patterson said. "Emotionally, I thought Oklahoma after that was
playing at a real high level."

Kansas State scored the next nine points and pulled within 65-50
on Laurie Koehn's 3-pointer from the right wing. Another 3-pointer
from Koehn and a leaner by Jessica McFarland cut the deficit to
69-57 with just over 6 minutes to play, but Kansas State could get
no closer.

Kendra Wecker scored 29 to lead the Wildcats, who lost their
second straight road game and fell a game behind Baylor in the Big
12 standings.

"I think if we're a basketball team that wants any chance of
winning games in this league, we've got to bring it night in and
night out, game in and game out," Patterson said. "We need to
answer that before we talk anything about where we might find
ourselves in the conference standings."

Chelsi Welch had 14 first-half points, and Leah Rush scored 12
for Oklahoma, which is 2-6 against ranked teams this season. The
Sooners, who won the Big 12 tournament last season, had lost four
of five and find themselves teetering on the NCAA tournament
bubble.

"We had to win a game," Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale said.
